definition.value: Any inhibitor of soluble epoxide hydrolase, a bifunctional enzyme that in humans is encoded by the EPHX2 gene.Found in both the cytosol and peroxisomes it binds to specific epoxides and converts them into the corresponding diols.
A phenylurea that is urea substituted by 1-acetylpiperidin-4-yl and 4-(trifluoromethoxy)phenyl groups at positions 1 and 3 respectively.
A phenylurea that is urea substituted by 1-(methylsulfonyl)piperidin-4-yl and 4-(trifluoromethoxy)phenyl groups at positions 1 and 3 respectively.
A phenylurea that is urea in which one of the hydrogens of each amino group is replaced by a 4-chlorophenyl group.
The ribonucleoside triphosphate oxoanion that is 5-methyl-CTP protonated to pH 7.3.
The ribonucleoside monophosphate oxoanion that is 5-methyl-CMP protonated to pH 7.3.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate in which the pyrimidine element is 5-methyluracil; major species at pH 7.3.
Major species at pH 7.3.
A member of the class of nectriapyrones that is nectriapyrone that carries a hydroxy group at position 4. It is a fungal metabolite isolated from Diaporthe gulyae.

An O-(S-acylpantetheine-4'-phosphoryl)serine(1-) residue in which the S-acyl group resulting from the deprotonation of the phosphate group of O-[S-(3,5,7,9,11,13-hexaoxotetradecanoyl)pantetheine-4'-phosphoryl]serine residue; major species at pH 7.3.
A naphtho-gamma-pyrone that is 3-methyl-2,3-dihydro-1H-naphtho[2,1-b]pyran-1-one substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3,6,7 and 9.

An organic anion that is the conjugate base of 3,6,7,9-tetrahydroxy-3-methyl-2,3-dihydro-1H-naphtho[2,1-b]pyran-1-one, arising from the deprotonation of the hydroxy group at position 6; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any 2,3-cis-enoyl CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
An O-(S-acylpantetheine-4'-phosphoryl)serine residue in which the S-acyl group is specified as 3,5,7,9,11,13-hexaaoxoheptadecanoyl.
Any glycosyloxyflavone that consists of a flavonol attached to a beta-D-glucosyl residue at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
An aryl phosphate that is tyramine in which the phenolic hydrogen at position 4 has been replaced by a phospho group.
Major species at pH 7.3. Published in  http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2013.07.029
Major species at pH 7.3. Published in http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2013.07.029
A class of glycerophospholipids in which a phosphatidyl group is esterified to the hydroxy group of dimethylpropanethiol.
An enolate anion resulting from the deprotonation of the enol group of andrastin E. Major species at pH 7.3. Published in http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2013.07.029
A 1,2-diacyl-phosphatidyldimethylpropanethiol in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 28 carbons and no double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-phosphatidyldimethylpropanethiol in which the two acyl groups both contain 14 carbons and no double bonds (tetradecanoyl).
A 1,2-diacyl-phosphatidyldimethylpropanethiol in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 32 carbons and 1 double bond.

A 1,2-diacyl-phosphatidyldimethylpropanethiol in which one of the acyl groups contains 14 carbons and no double bonds (tetradecanoyl) and the other contains 18 carbons and 1 double bond (octadecenoyl).

A 1,2-diacyl-phosphatidyldimethylpropanethiol in which the two acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 contain 14 carbons and no double bonds (tetradecanoyl) and 18 carbons and 1 double bond (octadecenoyl) respectively.
An enolate anion resulting from the deprotonation of the enol of andrastin D.Major species at pH 7.3. Published in http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2013.07.029
An enolate anion resulting from the deprotonation of the enol group of andrastin F. Major species at pH 7.3. Published in http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2013.07.029
An enolate anion resulting from the deprotonation of the enol group of andrastin C. Major species at pH 7.3. Published in http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2013.07.029

An enolate anion resulting from the deprotonation of the enol group of andrastin B. Major species at pH 7.3. Published in Tetrahedron, 2013, 69(38), 8199-8204. http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2013.07.029

An enolate anion resulting from the deprotonation of the enol group of andrastin A. Major species at pH 7.3. Published in Tetrahedron, 2013, 69(38), 8199-8204. http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2013.07.029

A member of the class of sulfamides that is sulfamide in which one of the amino groups has been substituted by a methyl group an an isopropyl group, while the other has been substituted by a 2-chloro-4-fluoro-5-[3-methyl-2,6-dioxo-4-(trifluoromethyl)-3,6-dihydropyrimidin-1(2H)-yl]benzoyl group. An important BASF herbicide, not registered in Europe but sold in USA, Canada and several other countries to control weeds in a wide range of food crops. Often mixed with other products such as glyphosate.

A secondary carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxylic acid group of 2,4,5-trimethyl-3-furoic acid with the amino group of aniline. An obsolete fungicide formerly used to control Basidiomycetes pathogens on cereal crops.

A member of the class of pyrimidines that is pyrimidine which is substituted at positions 2, 4, and 6 by 2,4-dichloroanilino, trifluoromethyl, and {2-[(1E)-1,3-dimethoxy-3-oxoprop-1-en-2-yl]benzyl}oxy groups, respectively. An acaricide used for the control of mites on citrus and cotton crops.
A ganglioside derivative derived from two GM1 skeletons linked through their amino nitrogen atoms by an adipoyl (hexanedioyl) group.
A ganglioside derivative derived from two GD1a skeletons linked through their amino nitrogen atoms by an adipoyl (hexanedioyl) group.
A ganglioside derivative derived from a GM1 skeleton linked to a GD1a skeleton through their respective amino nitrogen atoms by an adipoyl (hexanedioyl) group.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of (+)-vincadifformine. The major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of chlorfenac.
An ammonium salt comprising equimolar amounts of chlorfenac(1-) anions and ammonium cations. An obsolete herbicide.
An organic sodium salt comprising equimolar amounts of chlorfenac(1-) anions and sodium cations. An obsolete herbicide.
An aspidosperma alkaloid that is the methyl ester of 2,3-didehydroaspidospermidine-3-carboxylic acid.

A hydrochloride and hydrate of DRF053, an analogue (and more potent version) of roscovitine - it is 2 fold more potent against cyclin dependent kinase 5 (CDK5) and >150 times more potent against CDK1. Formula C23H27N7O.xHCl.yH2O.
An acetate ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of 15alpha-stemmadenine with the carboxy group of acetic acid.
A 9,10-dihydroxystearate in which the chiral carbon atoms at positions 9 and 10 have the R-configuration

A member of the class of 2,6-diaminopurines that is 2,6-diamiopurine which is substituted by an isopropyl group at position 9 and in which the amino groups at positions 2 and 6 are substituted by a 1-hydroxybutan-2-yl and 3-(pyridin-2-yl)phenyl groups, respectively (the R enantiomer). A cyclin dependent kinase inhibitor, widely used as its hydrochloride hydrate.
An organic anion arising from deprotonation of the hydroxy group of an enol.
